-- Shares in Popolare Milano sharply up as rights issue start
-- By Valentina Za
-- Mon May 05, 2014 03:18AM EDT
-- None



MILAN, May 5 (Reuters) - Shares in Banca Popolare di Milano (BPM) <PMII.MI> rose sharply in early trade on Monday as the Italian co-operative lender started offering rights to buy into a 500 million euro ($693.28 million) capital increase.

The rights <PMII_r.MI> rose 10 percent by 0706 GMT while shares in the bank were up 1.6 percent at 0.6585 euros, after soaring as much as 5 percent at the open. The Milan-based lender has priced the new shares at 0.43 euros each and is offering nine new shares for every 25 already owned. [ID:nL6N0NM69N] Analysts say the market should easily digest the share sale as cash-rich investors are betting on Italian banks encouraged by signs of an economic recovery in the country. Also on MOnday, shares in Banca Monte dei Paschi <BMPS.MI> fell 4.3 percent as the bank kicked off a reverse stock split ahead of a 5 billion euro capital increase starts.